<body>

<h1>@HI{{mou}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> <strong>@HI{{mou}}</strong>@Vta{{}}
<li> <strong>@HI{{mou}}</strong>@Vmasustem{{}}@HI{{mashita}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{mou}}</strong> means "already" and when combined with a verb in the past tense
the meaning is that the action specified by the verb has been completed.
</p>

<p>
In an affirmative interrogative sentence <strong>@HI{{mou}}</strong> means "yet" or "already".
</p>

<p>
In a negative sentence <strong>@HI{{mou}}</strong> means "not yet" or "not any longer".

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha<strong>mou</strong>@KJ{{sake}}wo@KJ{{drink}}masenn.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I won't drink <em>sake</em> any more.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
The answer to the question <strong>@HI{{mou}}</strong>@Vmasustem{{}}@HI{{mashitaka}} is @HI{{hai,mou}}@Vmasustem{{}}@HI{{mashita}} or
@HI{{iie,madadesu}}.


<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{mou@KJ{{baggage^thing}}wo@KJ{{escort}}rimashitaka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Have you sent the parcel yet?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{hai,@KJ{{escort}}rimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Yes I have.
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{iie,madadesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      No, not yet.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

An answer of the form @HI{{iie,}}@Vmasustem{{}}@HI{{masendeshita}} would imply that the task was not performed
rather than it has <em>not yet</em> been performed.
</p>

